        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S. E. R.</hi></placeName>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am delighted to hear that you intend working on the causes of variation.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is a grand subject, &amp; if I were not so old, I would take it up experimentally. But I am nearly worn out, &amp; will not attempt writing on any difficult &amp; complex subject again.— I fear that I have fallen into many mistakes in my work on the Power of movement in Plants, &amp; this ought to be a caution to me.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> With hearty thanks for your kind letter &amp; good wishes for your success in all your scientific undertakings</p>
<p>I remain | yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by an annotation at the top of the letter in an unknown hand and by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13402.xml">letter from Hugo de Vries, 15 October 1881</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13402.xml">letter from Hugo de Vries, 15 October 1881</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD had been reading a book that critiqued the results of experiments in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml"><hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi></ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11461.xml">Wiesner 1881</ref>). See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13411.xml">letter to Francis Darwin, 17 October 1881</ref>.</note>   
        </div>
    
